{
  "What does percent error measure in a science experiment?": "",
  "The accuracy of a measurement compared to the accepted value": "",
  "The total number of trials performed during an experiment": "",
  "The cost of the materials used during the experiment setup": "",
  "The time it takes to complete each trial of the experiment": "",
  "Percent error measures how far off an experimental (measured) value is from the accepted (true) value, expressed as a percentage.": "",
  "What is the formula for percent error?": "",
  "(Experimental value + Accepted value) / Accepted value x 100": "",
  "|Experimental value - Accepted value| / Accepted value x 100": "",
  "(Accepted value - Experimental value) x Accepted value x 100": "",
  "Experimental value / Accepted value + Accepted value x 100": "",
  "Percent error = |Experimental value - Accepted value| / Accepted value x 100. The absolute value bars ensure the result is always positive.": "",
  "What does a low percent error indicate about an experiment?": "",
  "The experiment had many significant errors in its design": "",
  "The experiment was not completed correctly by the student": "",
  "The experimental value is close to the accepted true value": "",
  "The experiment needs to be redone with completely new tools": "",
  "A low percent error means the experimental value is very close to the accepted value, indicating that the measurement was accurate and the experiment was performed well.": "",
  "Can percent error ever be a negative number?": "",
  "Yes, it is always a negative number in all experiments": "",
  "No, absolute value makes the result always positive": "",
  "Yes, but only when the experimental value is too high": "",
  "No, it is always exactly zero in properly done experiments": "",
  "Percent error uses absolute value in the numerator, which means the answer is always positive or zero. It measures the size of the error, not its direction.": "",
  "A student measures the boiling point of water as 99 degrees Celsius. The accepted value is 100 degrees Celsius. What is the percent error?": "",
