  "A student measures the density of aluminum as 2.5 g/cm cubed. The accepted density is 2.7 g/cm cubed. What is the percent error?": "",
  "About 7.4%": "",
  "About 14.8%": "",
  "About 0.20%": "",
  "About 92.6%": "",
  "|2.5 - 2.7| / 2.7 x 100 = 0.2 / 2.7 x 100 = 7.4%. The student's measurement was about 7.4% off from the true density of aluminum.": "",
  "A student measures the mass of a sample three times and gets 10.2 g, 10.3 g, and 10.2 g. The accepted mass is 12.0 g. Are these measurements precise, accurate, or both?": "",
  "Both precise and accurate because the values are close together": "",
  "Accurate but not precise because they are near the accepted value": "",
  "Precise but not accurate because they are close together but far from 12.0 g": "",
  "Neither precise nor accurate because they have differences between readings": "",
  "The measurements are precise because they are very close to each other (10.2, 10.3, 10.2). However, they are not accurate because they are far from the accepted value of 12.0 g.": "",
  "A student uses a balance that is not properly calibrated and always reads 2 grams too high. Every measurement she takes will be affected by what type of error?": "",
  "Random error, because every measurement is slightly different": "",
  "No error, because the balance is still providing a reading": "",
  "Systematic error, because every reading is shifted by the same amount": "",
  "Human error, because the student should know the balance is wrong": "",
  "This is a systematic error because the faulty calibration shifts every measurement by the same amount (2 grams too high). Systematic errors are consistent and predictable.": "",
  "Two students measure the boiling point of water. Student A gets 102 degrees Celsius and Student B gets 98 degrees Celsius. The accepted value is 100 degrees Celsius. Which student has the lower percent error?": "",
